Senior infantry regiments, often referred to as [foot guards](/Foot_guards), occupy a unique and elevated position within certain militaries, most notably the [British Army](/British_Army) and the [Canadian Army](/Canadian_Army). Their primary mandate encompasses rigorous military and combat operations, a role that demands the highest standards of training and readiness. However, their seniority is further underscored by a secondary, yet equally significant, set of responsibilities: [public duties](/Public_duties). These ceremonial functions are not mere posturing; they are a tangible reflection of the regiments' esteemed status, a visual testament to their historical significance and their enduring connection to the state and its symbols. Historically, the very concept of foot guards encompassed soldiers who fought on foot and also bore the responsibility of performing public duties, a dual role that has persisted through centuries.

The lineage of the British foot guards stretches back to the 17th century, where they were established not only as formidable infantry units but also as the dedicated [royal guards](/Royal_guards) tasked with the protection of the monarchy. This dual function cemented their prestige. In the 19th century, a similar tradition was adopted in Canada. The Canadian foot guards were formed, drawing direct inspiration from their British counterparts. This move was a deliberate acknowledgment of [Canada’s relationship with the monarchy](/Monarchy_of_Canada) and was intended to establish units capable of undertaking ceremonial duties within the nation's capital, Ottawa. While the British and Canadian examples are prominent, it is worth noting that other nations have, at various points in history, maintained units bearing the title of "foot guards." However, not all of these units necessarily held the distinction of being the senior infantry regiments within their respective forces, nor were they always tasked with the same blend of combat readiness and ceremonial public duties.

As of the current era, specifically looking towards 2025, the British Army continues to uphold its tradition with five distinct regiments of foot guards. The [Canadian Army Reserve](/Canadian_Army_Reserve), on the other hand, maintains two such regiments. While the majority of these foot guard units continue to operate within the [light infantry](/Light_infantry) or broader infantry roles, a notable shift has occurred within two of the five British foot guards regiments. These units have transitioned into [mechanised infantry](/Mechanised_infantry) roles, adapting their operational capabilities to modern warfare while retaining their ceremonial traditions.

### United Kingdom

Within the [British Army](/British_Army), five regiments of foot guards stand as pillars of military tradition and operational prowess. The [Grenadier Guards](/Grenadier_Guards), the [Coldstream Guards](/Coldstream_Guards), and the [Irish Guards](/Irish_Guards) are primarily specialized in [infantry](/Infantry) and [light infantry](/Light_infantry) roles, engaging in direct combat with a focus on agility and tactical deployment. In contrast, the [Scots Guards](/Scots_Guards) and the [Welsh Guards](/Welsh_Guards) have embraced a more modern approach, specializing in mechanised and light [mechanised infantry](/Mechanised_infantry) roles, integrating armored vehicles and advanced mobility into their operational framework. These five regiments collectively form the integral infantry component of the prestigious [Household Division](/Household_Division), a formation synonymous with both ceremonial duties and significant military contributions.

#### History

The genesis of the oldest foot guards regiment can be traced back to the tumultuous year of 1642. From their inception, these units were conceived as front-line combat troops, with their subsequent adoption of ceremonial public duties always serving as a secondary, albeit highly visible, function. Their role as [royal guards](/Royal_guards) to the [British monarch](/British_monarch) has endowed them with a unique tapestry of privileges and traditions that have been meticulously preserved and evolved over their extensive existence. It is a tradition that the reigning British monarch traditionally assumes the esteemed position of colonel-in-chief of each of the regiments within the Household Division, a symbolic and unifying bond.

The three most venerable regiments—the Grenadier Guards, the Coldstream Guards, and the Scots Guards—owe their establishment to the crucible of the [English Civil War](/English_Civil_War). The more recent additions, the Irish Guards and the Welsh Guards, were brought into being in the 20th century. The Irish Guards were formally created in 1900, a direct consequence of [Queen Victoria](/Queen_Victoria)'s profound admiration for the valor displayed by Irish units during the arduous [Second Boer War](/Second_Boer_War). The Welsh Guards followed in 1915, established by King [George V](/George_V) after it was brought to his attention that the Household Division lacked a dedicated representation from [Wales](/Wales). It is worth noting that a sixth regiment of foot guards, the [Guards Machine Gun Regiment](/Guards_Machine_Gun_Regiment), existed for a brief period following the conclusion of the [First World War](/First_World_War), before its eventual disbandment.

#### Public Duties

The regiments of the foot guards bear the significant responsibility of executing a range of public duties, with their most prominent role being the ceremonial mounting of the [King's Guard](/King%27s_Guard). This duty is performed at the iconic [St. James's Palace](/St._James%27s_Palace) and [Buckingham Palace](/Buckingham_Palace), the very heart of the British monarchy. Beyond these royal residences, they also undertake the solemn duty of [mounting](/Guard_mounting) the [Windsor Castle](/Windsor_Castle) Guard and the [Tower of London](/Tower_of_London) Guard, each of these locations holding profound historical and symbolic significance for the Crown. While the foot guards regiments are the primary custodians of these public duties, there are instances where they receive support from other units within the [British Armed Forces](/British_Armed_Forces) and even from contingents within the [Commonwealth of Nations](/Commonwealth_of_Nations), underscoring a broader sense of shared tradition and duty. Historically, the commitment of the foot guards extended to manning ten additional sentry posts scattered throughout [London](/London), including historically significant locations such as [Horse Guards](/Horse_Guards_(building)), [Savoy Prison](/Savoy_Place), and [Montagu House](/Montagu_House,_Bloomsbury), further illustrating the pervasive nature of their ceremonial responsibilities in the capital.

### Canada

Within the [Canadian Army Reserve](/Canadian_Army_Reserve), two distinguished regiments of foot guards stand as enduring symbols of military heritage: the [Governor General's Foot Guards](/Governor_General%27s_Foot_Guards) and the [Canadian Grenadier Guards](/Canadian_Grenadier_Guards). Both of these units trace their origins back to the 19th century, a testament to their long-standing presence in Canada's military landscape. These two regiments hold the distinction of being the senior reserve infantry regiments in Canada. Their training is rigorously focused on an infantry role, ensuring their readiness to support [Canadian Armed Forces](/Canadian_Armed_Forces) operations both domestically and internationally, providing crucial support to the [Regular Force](/Regular_Force) in its global endeavors. As integral components of Canada's household troops, these units serve as a potent symbol of the armed forces' connection to the [Canadian monarchy](/Canadian_monarchy), a relationship that is further emphasized by their mandate to perform public duties within the nation's capital, Ottawa. The Canadian Army Regular Force also once boasted a foot guard regiment, established in 1953 and known as the [Canadian Guards](/Canadian_Guards). However, this unit was reduced to nil strength in 1970 and subsequently reassigned to the army's [Supplementary Order of Battle](/Supplementary_Order_of_Battle), marking a significant, albeit temporary, chapter in the history of Canadian foot guards. Another unit, the [Royal Regiment of Canada](/Royal_Regiment_of_Canada), while formally a [line infantry](/Line_infantry) regiment, also adopts the distinctive uniform of a foot guard regiment. This tradition stems from its predecessor, the [Royal Grenadiers](/Royal_Grenadiers), which itself was uniformed in emulation of the esteemed British Grenadier Guards.

#### Public Duties

In addition to their fundamental infantry roles, the two Canadian regiments of foot guards are entrusted with significant ceremonial public duties. These duties are performed at key national landmarks such as [Rideau Hall](/Rideau Hall) and [Parliament Hill](/Parliament_Hill) in Ottawa, reinforcing their status as the nation's household troops. While both units actively participate in public duties within the capital, it is important to note that only the Governor General's Foot Guards are actually based in Ottawa; the Canadian Grenadier Guards are stationed in [Montreal](/Montreal). Beyond their direct involvement in ceremonial duties at Rideau Hall and other significant events for the [Governor General of Canada](/Governor_General_of_Canada), the Public Duties Company of the Governor General's Foot Guards also oversees the [Ceremonial Guard](/Ceremonial_Guard_(Canada)). This specialized subunit operates during the summer months and is open to members of the [Canadian Armed Forces](/Canadian_Armed_Forces) who express a desire to engage in ceremonial public duties. Service members who join the Ceremonial Guard don the uniforms of the two Canadian foot guard regiments, irrespective of their actual regimental or unit affiliation, thereby embodying the historical traditions and responsibilities traditionally carried out by the foot guard regiments.

### Other Historical Uses

#### Germany

Within the military structure of the [Kingdom of Prussia](/Kingdom_of_Prussia) and later the [Imperial German Army](/Imperial_German_Army) of the [German Empire](/German_Empire), several units were designated as *Garde-Regiment zu Fuß*, which translates literally to '[guard regiment on foot](/Literal_translation)'. These included notable regiments such as the [1st Foot Guards](/1st_Foot_Guards_(German_Empire)), the [3rd Foot Guards](/3rd_Foot_Guards_(German_Empire)), the [4th Foot Guards](/4th_Foot_Guards_(German_Empire)), and the [5th Foot Guards](/5th_Foot_Guards_(German_Empire)). The significance of these units was underscored by the fact that all Prussian princes were commissioned into the military through service with the 1st Foot Guards, highlighting its premier status.

#### Japan

In feudal Japan, particularly during the [Tokugawa shogunate](/Tokugawa_shogunate), the [hatamoto](/Hatamoto) were a class of high-ranking [samurai](/Samurai) who served their [daimyo](/Daimyo) directly. Among the hatamoto, there existed a subgroup known as the *kachi* or "Foot Guards." Alongside them were the *umamawari-shū*, or "Horse Guards." However, it is crucial to distinguish their roles: only the *umamawari-shū* were specifically tasked with serving as [bodyguards](/Bodyguard) for the daimyo. The *kachi*, while part of the elite guard structure, were not assigned ceremonial duties in the same capacity and were primarily engaged in combat as part of their training and progression towards higher positions within the samurai hierarchy. This distinction is vital in understanding the precise nature of these feudal military roles, as detailed in works such as Stephen Turnbull's *Samurai Vs Ashigaru*.

